Basic Geometry

Rectangle Midpoint

Consider a uniform rectangle. We reckon that the center of mass of this rectangle is equal to its midpoint, which is the intersection of its two diagonals. Of course, we know that the center of mass is just where and are the width and height of the rectangle respectively.

Triangle Midpoint Intersection

A segment bisector of a triangle is a line from a vertex to the opposite edge that cuts the edge at its center. We want to show that all three segment bisectors intersect at a point.

In the figure above, the inner green triangle is a triangle whose vertices are the outer triangles segment midpoints.
These vertices are indeed located at the segment midpoints because all triangles that make up the outer triangle are congruent (which is easily verified by noticing the alternating angles), and thus each connecting edge is equal in length, which is illustrated with pink in the figure above.
The orange, red, and blue lines are the respective diagonals of the parallelograms formed by a pair of two triangles. It follows that they are also segment bisectors of the outer triangle, as they connect a vertex of the green triangle (which are also segment midpoints of the outer triangle) to a vertex of the outer triangle. Furthermore, they are also segment bisectors of the inner green triangle because, as we've previously proven, the midpoint of both diagonals of a parallelogram intersect, so these lines also bisect the edges of the inner triangle and moves towards its vertices.
In general, a smaller triangle can be created by choosing the vertices to be the segment midpoints of its enclosing triangle.
As an aside, the enclosing triangle and the smaller triangle are similar. This can be deduced with alternating angles.
If we repeat this process, then we see that as the number of iterations increases, the area of the innermost triangle continues to get smaller. But, as we've established, they all share the same segment bisectors, it follows that as the number of triangles tends to , the area of the innermost triangle will tend towards , that is, the segment bisectors will meet at a point.
